  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>The Local Finder</strong> is the expanded local search results page that appears when a user clicks "More places" beneath the Local Pack in Google Search. It displays a full paginated list of all matching local businesses alongside a scrollable map, using the same GBP-based ranking algorithm as the Local Pack but extending visibility to positions 4 through 20 and beyond.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Access trigger</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Click "More places" in Local Pack</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking signals</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Same as Local Pack (GBP, reviews, citations)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local SEO conversations focus on the Local Pack — the 3-listing box in Google Search. But that's only a slice of the picture. Businesses ranked 4 through 20 in local results are still discoverable, driving website visits and calls from users who click "More places" to compare options. Understanding the Local Finder means competing for all positions, not just the top 3.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Local Finder?</h2>
        <p>The Local Finder is a dedicated Google search environment — not a standard SERP page — that activates when a user clicks "More places" beneath the Local Pack. It has two main panels:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Left panel:</strong> A scrollable list of business listings, typically 20 per page, each showing business name, star rating, review count, category, address, and hours. Users can filter by rating, hours, and other attributes.</li>
          <li><strong>Right panel:</strong> An interactive Google Map centred on the search area. Pins represent each business. As the user pans the map, the left-panel results update dynamically to show businesses in the visible map area.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The Local Finder URL format is distinct from standard search: it uses <code>google.com/search?...ludocid=...</code> parameters, and the ranking results are powered by the same Google Places infrastructure that drives Local Pack results. Critically, the Local Finder is also the interface Google uses when a user searches directly on Google Maps for a local business type.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Local Finder vs Google Maps — the connection</div>
          <p>When you search for "dentist Chicago" on Google Maps, you're in the Local Finder environment. The same business data, the same ranking signals, the same GBP-powered results. Ranking well in the Local Finder means ranking well on Google Maps — they are the same system.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the Local Finder matters for local SEO</h2>
        <p>The Local Pack gets the majority of local search clicks — studies show positions 1-3 capture roughly 44% of clicks for local intent queries. But Local Finder positions 4-20 are not dead traffic. Here's why they matter:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>High-consideration buyers compare options.</strong> Service categories like dentists, lawyers, contractors, and wedding venues attract searchers who deliberately click "More places" to compare 8-12 options. These are high-intent, high-value customers.</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile maps usage is growing.</strong> Users increasingly search directly within Google Maps rather than Google.com. Local Finder position 4-10 on Google Maps drives meaningful traffic for mobile-first service queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Position 4-10 is achievable faster than 1-3.</strong> Getting from Local Finder position 8 to position 4 is often achievable in 60-90 days with focused GBP and review work. Moving from position 4 to position 1 in the Local Pack can take 6-12 months.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor research lives here.</strong> The full Local Finder reveals every competitor ranking for a term — their review count, average rating, category selection, and GBP completeness. It's the most data-rich competitive intelligence view in local SEO.</li>
          <li><strong>Tracking Local Finder position separately is possible.</strong> Tools like BrightLocal and Whitespark track Local Finder rank (not just Pack rank), allowing more granular ranking measurement and trend data.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Local Finder ranking works</h2>
        <p>The Local Finder uses the same three-factor ranking algorithm as the Local Pack:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Relevance.</strong> How well your GBP primary and secondary categories match the query. A plumber who selected "Plumber" as primary category and "Emergency Plumber" and "Drainage Service" as secondary categories ranks higher for "drain unblocking" than a plumber with only a generic "Home Services" category.</li>
          <li><strong>Distance.</strong> Proximity between your business location (or service area polygon for SABs) and either the searcher's location or the location specified in the search query. This is calculated at the time of search, which is why Local Finder results differ for the same query from different starting points.</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence.</strong> The aggregated signal of how well-known and trusted your business is. Driven by review count, review recency, star rating, citation consistency, local backlinks, GBP completeness, and website authority signals.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>One key Local Finder nuance: the dynamic map. As a user pans the map to a different area, the Local Finder re-ranks results based on the new map centre. A business ranked 8th when viewing downtown Denver might rank 3rd when the map is panned two miles east because its proximity score increases. This is why geo-grid rank tracking (checking your position from multiple geographic points) matters for Local Finder optimisation.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Local Finder vs Local Pack vs Google Maps — what's the difference?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Local Pack</th><th>Local Finder</th><th>Google Maps</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
