              <tr><td><strong>Organic results visible?</strong></td><td>Yes (below Pack)</td><td>No — local-only view</td><td>No — local-only view</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Map interaction?</strong></td><td>Static mini-map</td><td>Interactive, pan to re-rank</td><td>Fully interactive</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Local Finder scenarios</h2>
        <p>Here is how three different search situations lead a user into the Local Finder and what ranking there means.</p>

        <h3>1. "Best dentist Denver" — high-comparison category</h3>
        <p>A searcher types "best dentist Denver" on Google. The Local Pack shows 3 results. The searcher clicks "More places" because they want to compare ratings and read reviews across multiple practices. They scroll through the Local Finder, filter by "Open now," and contact two dentists ranked 5th and 7th. Being ranked 4-10 in this category generates real patient inquiries.</p>

        <h3>2. Google Maps direct search — mobile user</h3>
        <p>A tourist opens Google Maps and types "pizza near me." They see a scrollable Local Finder list sorted by relevance and distance. The restaurant ranked 4th on Maps gets clicked because positions 1-3 are all too far. Mobile users frequently interact with positions 4-8 in Maps searches.</p>

        <h3>3. Contractor comparison — high-value service</h3>
        <p>A homeowner needs a roofing contractor and searches "roofing contractor San Diego." They click "More places" and spend 10 minutes reading through the Local Finder, comparing review counts (a contractor with 180 reviews vs one with 22), checking photos, and looking at service areas. Being in the Local Finder with 150+ reviews and complete GBP data won this contractor a $12,000 job.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local Finder vs local organic results — which matters more?</h2>
        <p>Both matter, and they are separate ranking systems. Local Finder rankings come from your Google Business Profile. Local organic rankings come from your website's on-page SEO and link profile. The most effective local SEO strategy targets both simultaneously.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Prioritise Local Finder when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Your business is service-category based</li>
              <li>You rely on phone calls and walk-ins</li>
              <li>Your GBP is incomplete or review-poor</li>
              <li>You're in a mobile-heavy industry</li>
              <li>Competitors have strong GBPs</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Prioritise local organic when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Your queries are informational (how-to)</li>
              <li>You have multiple service lines or pages</li>
              <li>You want long-term content authority</li>
              <li>Competition in Local Pack is very high</li>
              <li>You run an e-commerce + local hybrid</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for ranking in the Local Finder</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Select the most specific GBP primary category available.</strong> "Emergency Plumber" outranks "Plumber" for emergency queries. "Italian Restaurant" outranks "Restaurant." Browse the full Google category list and choose the most granular match for your core service.</li>
          <li><strong>Add 5-10 secondary categories.</strong> These expand your relevance footprint without diluting primary category authority. A dental practice can add "Cosmetic Dentist," "Orthodontist," and "Teeth Whitening Service" as secondary categories.</li>
          <li><strong>Track Local Finder position separately from Local Pack position.</strong> Use geo-grid tools (BrightLocal, Local Falcon) to map your Local Finder rank from 25-64 points across your service area. This reveals geographic ranking gaps — pockets where you rank 12th that could be 4th with targeted work.</li>
          <li><strong>Build review velocity — not just count.</strong> Google's freshness weighting means 30 reviews received in the past 60 days outperform 300 reviews with the last batch being 18 months ago. Set up a consistent post-service review request system.</li>
          <li><strong>Complete every GBP attribute relevant to your category.</strong> Attributes like "Women-led," "LGBTQ+ friendly," "Wheelchair accessible," "Free WiFi," and "Accepts credit cards" are used as Local Finder filters. Missing attributes means you're invisible to users who apply those filters.</li>
          <li><strong>Add GBP photos monthly.</strong> Google's algorithm gives preference to GBPs with recent photo uploads. Interior shots, exterior shots, staff photos, and before/after work photos all count. Aim for 3-5 new photos per month minimum.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — ignoring positions 4-10</div>
          <p>Many local SEO campaigns declare success when a business enters the Local Pack (top 3) and stop optimising. But positions 4-10 in the Local Finder receive real clicks in comparison-heavy categories. And Local Pack positions are more volatile than Local Finder positions — a business that slips from 3rd to 4th after a local algorithm update hasn't disappeared, it's still highly visible in the Local Finder.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Local Finder mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Not tracking Local Finder position at all.</strong> Many businesses only track Pack rank and miss the full competitive picture that Local Finder data provides.</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword-stuffing the business name on GBP.</strong> Adding city or service keywords to your GBP business name violates Google guidelines and can result in suspension — removing you from Local Finder entirely.</li>
          <li><strong>Setting a too-large service area for SABs.</strong> Service area businesses that set an overly broad service area get penalised for poor distance relevance. Set your service area to the realistic reach where you actually serve customers.</li>
          <li><strong>Leaving GBP Q&amp;A unanswered.</strong> The Q&amp;A section appears in Local Finder listings. Unanswered questions get answered by the public (including competitors). Pre-populate Q&amp;A with your 10 most common customer questions.</li>
          <li><strong>Not responding to map spam.</strong> Competitor GBP listings with fake addresses or keyword-stuffed names are reportable via Google's Business Redressal form. Cleaning up spam in your category directly improves your Local Finder position.</li>
        </ul>

